## Debrief after level 7: replay-player unification + higher-order candidate

Comparing `play_level_7` to the earlier players exposed one drift: levels 6
and 7 (installed by harness recovery) called the low-level `execute_path`
primitive with an inline literal path, while level 5 used the strategy-level
`solve_by_replay` leg for the exact same skill. Refactored: all three
replay-style players (5, 6, 7) now call `solve_by_replay` -- the skill lives
ONCE in legs.py and players.py is pure thin composition. No behaviour change
(`solve_by_replay` == `execute_path` + return-path), confirmed by rerunning
`gkm_try.py` with levels >= 7.

Recurring composition pattern (candidate higher-order leg): every player is
now an instance of ONE shape --

    solve_with_plan(env, plan_source) := path = plan_source(env); execute_path(env, path)

with three plan sources so far:
  - `lambda env: LITERAL_PATH`            -> solve_by_replay   (levels 5, 6, 7)
  - `find_winning_path` (raw frames)      -> solve_by_search   (levels 1, 2)
  - `detect_noise_mask` + masked search   -> solve_masked      (levels 3, 4)

That is 7/7 players, 3 distinct plan sources. If a 4th plan source appears
(e.g. the map-then-controller planner used offline for level 7's fog level),
promote `solve_with_plan(env, plan_source)` into legs.py and re-express
solve_by_replay/solve_by_search/solve_masked as partial applications of it.
The deeper invariant making this work: the game family is deterministic and
world-ticks only on (successful) moves, so "plan on clones offline, commit a
literal path" is always a valid decomposition.
